    %h1 jQuery.support
  %div{"data-role" => "content", "data-theme" => "c", :id => "jQuery.support1"}
    %h2.jq-clearfix.roundTop.section-title
      %span.name jQuery.support
      %span.returns
        Returns:
        %a.return{:href => "http://docs.jquery.com/Types#Object"} Object
    .entry-details
      %p.desc
        %strong> Description:
        A collection of properties that represent the presence of different browser features or bugs.
      %ul.signatures
        %li.signature{:id => "jQuery.support"}
          %h4.name
            %span.versionAdded>
              version added:
              %a{:href => "/category/version/1.3/"} 1.3
            jQuery.support
      .longdesc
        %p
          Rather than using
          %code $.browser
          to detect the current user agent and alter the page presentation based on which browser is running, it is a good practice to perform
          = succeed "." do
            %strong feature detection
          This means that prior to executing code which relies on a browser feature, we test to ensure that the feature works properly. To make this process simpler, jQuery performs many such tests and makes the results available to us as properties of the
          %code jQuery.support
          object.
        %p The values of all the support properties are determined using feature detection (and do not use any form of browser sniffing).
        %blockquote
          %p Following are a few resources that explain how feature detection works:
          %ul
            %li
              %a{:href => "http://peter.michaux.ca/articles/feature-detection-state-of-the-art-browser-scripting"} http://peter.michaux.ca/articles/feature-detection-state-of-the-art-browser-scripting
            %li
              %a{:href => "http://www.jibbering.com/faq/faq_notes/not_browser_detect.html"} http://www.jibbering.com/faq/faq_notes/not_browser_detect.html
            %li
              %a{:href => "http://yura.thinkweb2.com/cft/"} http://yura.thinkweb2.com/cft/
        %p
          While jQuery includes a number of properties, developers should feel free to add their own as their needs dictate. Many of the
          %code jQuery.support
          properties are rather low-level, so they are most useful for plugin and jQuery core development, rather than general day-to-day development.
        %p
          The tests included in
          %code jQuery.support
          are as follows:
        %ul
          %li
            %code> boxModel
            \: Is equal to true if the page is rendering according to the
            %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/REC-CSS2/box.html"} W3C CSS Box Model
            (is currently false in IE 6 and 7 when they are in Quirks Mode). This property is null until document ready occurs.
          %li
            %code> cssFloat
            \: Is equal to true if the name of the property containing the CSS float value is .cssFloat, as defined in the
            = succeed "." do
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/DOM-Level-2-Style/css.html#CSS-CSS2Properties-cssFloat"} CSS Spec
            (It is currently false in IE, it uses styleFloat instead).
          %li
            %code> hrefNormalized
            \: Is equal to true if the
            %code .getAttribute()
            method retrieves the
            %code href
            attribute of elements unchanged, rather than normalizing it to a fully-qualified URL. (It is currently false in IE, the URLs are normalized).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/DOM-Level-3-Core/core.html#ID-666EE0F9"} DOM l3 spec
          %li
            %code> htmlSerialize
            \: Is equal to true  if the browser is able to serialize/insert
            %code &lt;link&gt;
            elements using the
            %code .innerHTML
            property of elements. (is currently false in IE).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/2008/WD-html5-20080610/serializing.html#html-fragment"} HTML5 wd
          %li
            %code> leadingWhitespace
            \: Is equal to true if the browser inserts content with .innerHTML exactly as providedâ€”specifically, if leading whitespace characters are preserved. (It is currently false in IE 6-8).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/2008/WD-html5-20080610/dom.html#innerhtml0"} HTML5 wd
          %li
            %code> noCloneEvent
            \: Is equal to true  if cloned DOM elements are created without event handlers (that is, if the event handlers on the source element are not cloned). (It is currently false in IE).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/DOM-Level-2-Events/events.html#Events-Registration-interfaces-h3"} DOM l2 spec
          %li
            %code> objectAll
            \: Is equal to true  if the
            %code .getElementsByTagName()
            method returns all descendant elements when called with a wildcard argument ('*'). (It is currently false in IE 7 and IE 8).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/WD-DOM/level-one-core.html#ID-745549614"} DOM l1 spec
          %li
            %code> opacity
            \: Is equal to true if a browser can properly interpret the opacity style property. (It is currently false in IE, it uses alpha filters instead).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-color/#transparency"} CSS3 spec
          %li
            %code> scriptEval
            \: Is equal to true if inline scripts are automatically evaluated and executed when inserted to the document using standard DOM manipulation methods, such as
            %code appendChild()
            and
            = succeed "." do
              %code createTextNode()
            (It is currently false in IE, it uses
            %code .text
            to insert executable scripts).
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/2008/WD-html5-20080610/tabular.html#script"} HTML5 WD
          %li
            %code> style
            \: Is equal to true if inline styles for an element can be accessed through the DOM attribute called style, as required by the DOM Level 2 specification. In this case,
            %code .getAttribute('style')
            can retrieve this value; in Internet Explorer,
            %code .cssText
            is used for this purpose.
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://www.w3.org/TR/DOM-Level-2-Style/css.html#CSS-ElementCSSInlineStyle"} DOM l2 Style spec
          %li
            %code> tbody
            \: Is equal to true if an empty
            %code &lt;table&gt;
            element can exist without a
            %code &lt;tbody&gt;
            element. According to the HTML specification, this sub-element is optional, so the property should be true in a fully-compliant browser. If false, we must account for the possibility of the browser injecting
            %code &lt;tbody&gt;
            tags implicitly. (It is currently false in IE, which automatically inserts
            %code tbody
            if it is not present in a string assigned to
            = succeed ")." do
              %code innerHTML
            %div
              %a{:href => "http://dev.w3.org/html5/spec/Overview.html#the-table-element"} HTML5 spec
